## Chapter Two: The City of Hidden Doors

Ashara was a city built on layers.

Under the tiles of the market square, under the foundations of the warehouses, there were rooms and halls that no one visited for generations. The city planners had said the old places were unsafe. The priests said they were forbidden. The children called them the Forgotten Ways.

But the Forgotten Ways were not truly forgotten—not by everyone. There were those who remembered, who kept the old maps and the older stories, who whispered about the underground passages in tones that were half reverence and half warning. Among the lantern-makers, the knowledge was passed down like a trade secret, from master to apprentice, each one learning the layout of the tunnels and chambers that honeycombed the earth beneath the city. There were three levels of the Forgotten Ways, each deeper and more dangerous than the last. The first level was merely old—old storerooms and old workshops, abandoned when the city grew upward instead of outward. The second level was older still, dating back to the earliest days of the settlement, when the first wanderers had dug shelters into the soft stone. But the third level... the third level was ancient, so ancient that no one knew who had built it or why.

The walls of the third level were not stone, but something harder, something that seemed to absorb light rather than reflect it. Strange symbols were carved into the surfaces—spirals and circles and patterns that resembled writing but followed no alphabet Nira had ever seen. The air down there was different, too: cold and still and faintly sweet, like the inside of a flower. And the silence was deeper than anything above—a silence that seemed to have weight and texture, pressing against the ears like deep water.

Nira had been only once, when she was very young, before the Silence came. An old lantern-maker named Corwen had taken her by the hand and led her down through a trapdoor in the floor of his workshop. She remembered the feeling of the stairs beneath her feet—slick with moisture, worn smooth by centuries of footsteps—and the way the lantern light seemed to shrink the further they went, until it was no bigger than a firefly in the immensity of the dark. Corwen had shown her a chamber deep in the second level, where the walls were covered with paintings. They depicted the founding of Ashara—the wanderers crossing the desert, the first fire, the raising of the Great Lantern—but they were different from the stories Nira had heard. In the paintings, the founders were not triumphant. They were afraid. They huddled together in the darkness, their faces lit by a single flame, and behind them, in the corners of the stone, shapes moved that were not quite human and not quite animal.

"What are those?" Nira had asked, pointing to the shadows.

"That which was here before us," Corwen said. "That which the stories keep at bay."

He never took her down again.

Nira had always been curious about forbidden places. When the silence spread and strangers came to the city gate with questions and ancient books, she began to understand that the old stories had been warning them all along.

The strangers arrived five days after the Silence fell. They came through the eastern gate in a group of seven, dressed in long coats of a material Nira had never seen—something between cloth and leather that shimmered like oil on water. They carried packs on their backs and books in their hands, and they spoke to each other in a language that was not quite Asharan, though it was close enough that bits and pieces could be understood. The city guard, reduced now to a skeleton crew of men who patrolled in silence, watched them with hollow eyes and said nothing.

Nira first saw them from the roof of her mother's stall, where she often went to watch the lanterns at dusk. The leader of the group was a tall woman with silver hair and a scar that ran from her left eyebrow to her jaw—a wound, Nira would later learn, received from a Silence-beast in the northern territories, though no one in Ashara knew what a Silence-beast was. The woman walked with the confidence of someone who had crossed great distances and expected to find what she was looking for. Behind her followed two men, one old and bent, the other young and restless-eyed. Then came the others, each carrying the weight of the journey on their shoulders.

The strangers set up camp in the market square, which was empty now—no vendors, no crowds, only the faint rustling of dry leaves blown by a wind that seemed to come from nowhere and go nowhere. They unpacked their books and spread them across the cobblestones, reading by the light of a chemical lamp that burned with a pale blue flame. Nira crept closer, drawn by a curiosity she could not name, and listened.

They spoke of the Silence as if it were a known quantity—as if it had a history, a nature, a weakness. The silver-haired woman, who introduced herself as Elara (though Nira would later learn this was not her true name), explained to her companions that the Silence was not a curse or a punishment but a natural phenomenon—the result of a fundamental imbalance in the world.

"Stories are the binding force of reality," Elara said, her voice carrying the faint accent of the northern provinces. "Every tale told creates a thread in the fabric of existence. When enough threads are severed, the fabric begins to unravel. The Silence is what comes through the holes."

One of her companions, the old man, shook his head. "But the stories did not stop being true simply because people stopped telling them," he said. "Where did the threads go?"

"They remain, in the places where the stories originated. But without the energy of retelling, they weaken. The Silence feeds on that weakness."

Nira listened to this exchange with growing excitement. Here were people who understood—who had encountered the Silence before and had survived. She wanted to call out to them, to ask them to explain more, but she was afraid. She was afraid that if she revealed herself, the strangers would not believe her—that they would look at her the way most people looked at her now, as a curiosity, an oddity, a remnant of a world that no longer existed.

Instead, she returned to her mother's stall and sat in the dark, turning over their words in her mind. The idea that stories were not just entertainment but a fundamental force—that they held the world together—resonated with her in a way she could not explain. It confirmed what she had always felt, what she had heard in the ticking of Maren's clocks and the breathing of Tamsin's clay. Sound was not a luxury. It was a necessity.

The lantern-maker, named Haim, could not speak, but he could still write. He scratched letters into a scrap of parchment with fingers that moved as though haunted.

"Light remembers," he wrote. "The silence feeds on what is forgotten. There is a door beneath the southern square. Only the one who listens can find it. Take the lantern. Trust the song in your bones."

Nira's heart beat harder. Trust, she thought, because that was what listening meant; it meant believing in something invisible.

She took one of Haim's lanterns. It was heavier than it looked, its glass glowing faintly from within. As she carried it through the streets, she felt the silence press against her ears like heavy velvet. The air smelled of cinnamon and old paper. Children moved in slow arcs, as if the world itself had become syrup.

Beneath the southern square, Nira descended not by stairs but by a narrow passage that angled sharply downward into the earth. The walls here were not of stone but of something older—compressed sediment and the fossilized remains of creatures that had lived millions of years before the first humans had walked this land. The passage twisted and turned, sometimes widening into small chambers where the air was thick with mineral smell, sometimes narrowing to a width that forced Nira to turn sideways and slide through with her arms extended before her like the wings of a bird.

She had been told by Corwen that the first level was merely a network of old cellars and storage rooms, built by the city's founders to store food and supplies during the long months of winter. The second level was older—the remains of a civilization that had predated Ashara, though almost nothing was known about its builders. But the passage Nira followed did not go to the first or second level. It went deeper, to a place that Corwen had never shown her—a place that the old lantern-maker had admitted he did not fully understand.

In a corner hidden by cracked tiles and ivy—though how ivy had come to grow so deep underground was a mystery that Nira did not pause to consider—Nira found a seam in the stone. When she placed the lantern against it, the glass flared with a violet light. The wall grew thin and an outline appeared—a doorway that was not really there until she believed it.

The door opened with a sigh.
